			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
2) Reporting is anonymous and not tied to anything which could identify the end user  
<br />

<br />
We all know that's @#%$. Sure, it may not report it with every submission, but your cable box has the cable equivalent of a MAC address, and if they really want to check up on you specifically I'm sure they can do it. It's a proprietary network too, which means their security is probably crappy. Would love to hear from a cable network engineer on this if there are any reading. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I can't speak for non-tivo brand devices, however all the Tivo-branded devices (Tivo, Directivo, etc) do reporting via the dialup connection that happens a few times a week.  The only user-identifiable data in the viewing-data dump that's transmitted is zip code, verified by third parties.  We're told that the data file is imported and discarded once received, and it's source (caller id, tivo unit #, etc) is not tracked.  When the tivo does it's dialup, it's actually an private IP connection to the tivo network -- it does it's maintenance via one http server, and then it transmitts the log data to a 2nd server.  The data tracked is channel data, recorded shows, remote control keypresses tied to show being watched (to know about pausing, ff thru commercial, whatever), etc.
<br />

<br />
Additionally, you can opt out of reporting by asking them not to track your unit, and your unit will no longer send tracking data after the next call in.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
