	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><span class="name"><a name="49070"></a><b>polad1</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Lurker
		
		<br />Joined: 10 Nov 2003<br />Posts: 49</span></td>
		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=49070&amp;sid=a25f15a8838d203a19941b8e1c95cb4c#49070"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon Feb 09, 2004 9:05 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Big brother amok?</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=49070&amp;sid=a25f15a8838d203a19941b8e1c95cb4c"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Cobee wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Who the f*** actually thought their innocent little network connected anonymous usage statistic gathering Janet boob recycling hard drive in a box wasn't betraying their thinly veiled privacy?  Is it really that intrusive anyway?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You know you pay TiVo to use their service AND you allow them to collect data from you.  It's like paying to be in a clinical test. They should be paying you for using their service.  The data you give them are worth at least a few thousand dollars, since they sell it to broadcasting corporations, ad agencies and other third parties.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, that's how the intrusive tactics begin. They come in and start cataloging seemingly innocuous details about your life, like which TV shows you watched last month. When people start showing they don't care, they start cataloging more things, then more and more and more.  Eventually a small group of entities will have information on what you buy, where you go, what you read, what you listen to on the radio, who you call on the phone, etc.  Your anonymity and privacy will be void.
<br />

<br />
Data is worth a lot of money these days.  One of the biggest problems in releasing information for others (government, advertisers, research institutes) to use is keeping the sources anonymous.  If you cross a few databases of "anonymously sourced" information, you'd be surprised how quickly that anonymity falls away.  The data itself may seem useless as a whole, but you wouldn't believe what some statistical applications can infer from that data.
<br />

<br />
I'm not trying to be alarmist, but privacy, just like rights, isn't yanked away instantly.  It erodes.  And when you're paying someone to intrude on your privacy it only invites others to do the same.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
