			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Hells bells... One of the hyped reasons for cable back in the 70s was that it would do away with advertisements. What a crock. Ads are everywhere, including those pop overs. 
<br />

<br />
There was a stink last year (or maybe year before last) in europe about tv networks placing ads on the soccer fields (like the yellow line on football games, but just think about whole ads getting displayed the whole game that way). 
<br />

<br />
I predict that cable boxes will record and play commercials just for you, after all the demographics are figured out. So while all the neighbors are seeing "come on down to McD's for half price happy meals" you will see, "hey dirty old man, come down to McD's cus there will be lots of kids for you to leer at." If your girlfriend watches too much queer eye for the straight guy, your cable box may play ads for the local @#%$ bar instead of budweiser babe ads. Your neighbors see "this bud's for you, mr bad toupee wearer" and you see "this bud's for you, mr underwear fashion modeler."
<br />

<br />
Second prediction. PVRs will be programmed in the future to make you sit and watch several ads before you can see anything. Think of those ads on DVDs that many players will not let you skip at the beginning of a disc. Imagine if you have a multiple choice quiz after the ads to make sure you watched them before you can watch the game, or look at the weather channel. TV networks are sueing the makers of PVRs because you can skip commercials. 
<br />

<br />
Third prediction. Subscription cable channels will start getting money from advertisers to place ads into the movies, overwriting the placements that other advertisers placed into the original movie. Example: coke pays big bucks for coke to be all over the movie; Pepsi pays hbo to digitally replace all the cokes with pepsis. They will pretend this is to prevent rising subscription fees, which will go up anyway.
<br />

<br />
Polad is right, the info that folks in the US are willing to give away (for nothing) is vastly greater than folks in europe are willing to part with. If you filled out your real name, address and email when you got one of those supermarket cards, you are a chump. Supermarkets raise their prices and pretend to offer you a discount (omg! its the same price before there were member cards) when you present them with the "club card." When you fill out the info for some alleged online contest, do you realise you are signing up for a lifetime of spam? All the holders of the data need to do, is post somewhere on their site that they changed their data policy and you can do nothing with your data. In europe, you own the data about you. In the US, the keeper of the database owns the data about you.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
